U.S. Index Futures Are Little Changed Before Economic Data; FedEx Declines

-- B y   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 
2011-02-15T13:10:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/u-s-index-futures-are-little-changed-before-economic-data-fedex-declines.html
U.S. stock-index futures drifted
between gains and losses after the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index
climbed to its highest level since June 2008, as investors
awaited reports on retail sales and manufacturing.  S&P 500 futures expiring in March slipped 0.1 percent to
1,326.3 at 8:07 a.m. in  New York . The benchmark gauge for U.S.
equities has gained 97 percent from a 12-year low in March 2009
amid government stimulus measures and higher-than-estimated
corporate profits. Dow Jones Industrial Average futures loss
less than 0.1 percent to 12,215 today, while futures on the
Nasdaq-100 Index slipped 0.1 percent to 2,378.75.  “The rally is justified, even if there is potential in the
short term for some profit taking,” said Henk Potts, an equity
strategist at Barclays Wealth in  London , which oversees $239
billion. “Investors need to detach themselves from the
uncertain macro environment and concentrate on what is still a
positive corporate picture.”  The advance has pushed the S&P 500 to 15.9 times the
reported operating earnings of its companies on Feb. 11, the
highest valuation since June. Earnings-per-share have topped
analysts’ estimates at about 73 percent of the 352 companies in
the  S&P 500  that reported results since Jan. 10, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg.  Retail Sales  Retail sales probably increased in January for a seventh
month as post-holiday promotions lured U.S. shoppers, economists
said before a report at 8:30 a.m. in  Washington  today.  The projected 0.5 percent gain in purchases would follow a
0.6 percent December increase, according to the median forecast
of 78 economists surveyed by Bloomberg News. Other data may show
the cost of imported goods climbed and manufacturing in the New
York region grew at the fastest pace in eight months.  U.S. Steel Corp. gained 2.7 percent to $61.95 in early New
York trading. The biggest American producer of the metal by
volume was raised to “buy” from “neutral” at Goldman Sachs,
which raised its earnings estimates for the company on the back
of lower expected costs and higher utilization rates.  Jakks Pacific Inc., the Malibu, California-based
manufacturer of toys, fell 0.3 percent to $18.37 in New York.
Per-share earnings this year may reach as much as $1.35, Jakks
Pacific said, missing the $1.52 prediction in a survey of
analysts.  Marriott International Inc. may be active. The owner of the
JW Marriott and Ritz-Carlton brands said it will spin off its
timeshare unit to allow investors to choose between its hotel
management and property development businesses. The shares
didn’t trade in  Europe .  To contact the reporters on this story:
Alexis Xydias in London at 
 axydias@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:  David Merritt  at 
 dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 